Theory: 
In Java, the StringBuffer class is a mutable sequence of characters used for creating and manipulating strings. Unlike the String class, StringBuffer allows modification of string content without creating a new object, making it memory efficient for multiple string operations. StringBuffer provides several built-in 
methods such as append (adding text at the end), insert (adding text at a specific position), replace (replacing part of the string), delete (removing part of the 
string), and reverse (reversing the entire string). This experiment demonstrates the practical usage of these methods in real-time string manipulation.
*/

public class Exp5b {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Append method - adds text at the end
        StringBuffer sb1 = new StringBuffer("NINJAL");
        sb1.append("PARDESHI");
        System.out.println("After append: " + sb1);

        // Insert method - inserts text at a specified index
        StringBuffer sb2 = new StringBuffer("NINJAL");
        sb2.insert(1, "JAVA");
        System.out.println("After insert: " + sb2);

        // Replace method - replaces characters from index 1 to 2 with "JAVA"
        StringBuffer sb3 = new StringBuffer("NINJAL");
        sb3.replace(1, 3, "JAVA");
        System.out.println("After replace: " + sb3);

        // Delete method - deletes characters from index 1 to 2
        StringBuffer sb4 = new StringBuffer("NINJAL");
        sb4.delete(1, 3);
        System.out.println("After delete: " + sb4);

        // Reverse method - reverses the entire string
        StringBuffer sb5 = new StringBuffer("NINJAL");
        sb5.reverse();
        System.out.println("After reverse: " + sb5);
    }
}
